Here's a complete example for a C# MCP server that wraps a REST API:

---

## Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by their ID from the REST API.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID to look up")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Create a new user in the system.")]
    public async Task<string> CreateUser(
        [Description("Display name for the new user")] string name,
        [Description("Email address")] string email,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { name, email });
        var content = new StringContent(payload, System.Text.Encoding.UTF8, "application/json");
        var response = await httpClient.PostAsync("/users", content, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

---

## `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

// Register HttpClient with a base address for the API
builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK has two injection styles:

| Style | Class type | How services are resolved |
|-------|-----------|--------------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class (shown above) | Services injected via primary constructor. Class is instantiated per-call. |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | DI services appear as method params alongside user params. |

**Key rules:**
- Parameters of types registered in DI (e.g., `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`) are **automatically resolved** and **never exposed** in the tool's JSON schema sent to the LLM.
- Only parameters with `[Description]` attributes appear in the schema.
- `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, and `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` are also auto-injected framework types.

In the example above, `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` come from DI via the constructor. The LLM only sees `userId`, `name`, and `email` as callable parameters.

**To scaffold this project from scratch:**
```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n MyApiServer
# or manually:
dotnet new console -n MyApiServer
cd MyApiServer
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol
```
